Headlines.Headline: Buy Now or Pay Later

PARAGRAPH.#text: What's the price of a month's indecision? When it comes to housing, more than $6,000. That's how much someone locking in Freddie Mac 30-year financing for a $250,000 home a month ago would have saved versus waiting until this week. With 20% down, excluding taxes and insurance, the Freddie Mac calculator puts monthly payments at $1,026 with the 30-year fixed rate at 4.61%. A month ago, with the rate at 4.17%, it was $975. That $51 extra adds up to $6,120 if the buyer hangs on to the house for ten years. Not the end of the world. But no following wind for a housing recovery, either. Hot air after all? More than a year after Air Products & Chemicals went after rival AirGas, it unveiled a "best and final" offer at $70 a share Thursday. That's $4.50 above the most recent offer, and yet Airgas shares fell 6% to $61.84. We hear arbitrage investors, fearing the deal will now fail, were crowding the exits.

Headlines.SeoHeadline: OVERHEARD: All in the Timing
Headlines.Headline: All in the Timing

PARAGRAPH.#text: Talk about timing. In February, a few days after Airgas stock was pounded by the company reporting weaker-than-expected earnings, Air Products & Chemicals swooped in with a $5.1 billion hostile offer. What a few days earlier would have been a decent premium looked positively rich. Airgas was up in arms, claiming the offer was too low.Then in late March, four analysts cut their outlooks for Airgas within a three-day period. While Airgas hadn't announced any news, the analysts cited weather-related disruptions to sales, higher-than-expected computer-system costs and a weaker economic recovery in Airgas's markets. The cuts reduced this quarter's consensus earnings estimate to 67 cents a share from 69 cents a share. If the company blows through estimates when it announces earnings this week, it could improve its prospects for fending off the bid. And Airgas will owe the analysts a pat on the back for deflating expectations.

reported first-quarter earnings that beat expectations, but the retailer lowered its second-quarter and full-year earnings targets, citing the continued softness in same-store sales and economic uncertainty. After the closing bell Friday, the retailer reported net income of $24.8 million, or 18 cents per share, compared with $32.8 million, or 25 cents per share, in the year-earlier period. Revenue came in at $1.22 billion vs. $1.15 billion last year. Analysts had been expecting Nordstrom to earn 14 cents per share, according to First Call/Thomson Financial. Going forward, Nordstrom sees second-quarter earnings per share in the range of 28 cents to 31 cents. Analysts had pegged Nordstrom to earn 35 cents per share. giddy.
